of challenges to the man/woman binary on the African continent and brings together gender, queer, and postcolonial studies to question the stability of sex. It examines issues including why transsexuals' sex transitions were encouraged under apartheid and illegal during the political transition to democracy and how butch lesbians and drag queens in urban townships reshape race and gender. Sex in Transition challenges the dominance of theoretical frameworks based in the global North, drawing on fifteen years of research in South Africa to define the parameters of a new transnational transgender and sexuality studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aGender identity -- South Africa. 0aGender identityzSouth Africa. 0aIntersexuality -- South Africa. 0aIntersexualityzSouth Africa. 0aTranssexualism -- South Africa -- History. 0aTranssexualismzSouth AfricaxHistory. 0aTranssexuals -- Legal status, laws, etc. -- South Africa. 0aTranssexualsxLegal status, laws, etczSouth Africa. 4aArea Studies : African Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Gender Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Queer Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438444086423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438444086/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles